Rotary District 9110, has leveraged on its Water, Sanitation and Hygiene, (WASH) Programme to create awareness on the importance of hygienic habits, especially hand washing with respect to the advent of the Corona-Virus Disease. Speaking at WASH Programme in Lagos, District Governor, District 9110, Rotarian Jide Akeredolu, said that the importance of hygienic habits like hand-washing cannot be over emphasised with the advent of the Corona Virus pandemic. Akeredolu stated, “We are encouraged to help create healthier communities by supplying clean water and sanitation facilities to prevent the spread of infectious diseases. When people have access to clean water and sanitation, waterborne diseases decrease, children stay healthier and attend school more regularly, and mothers can spend less time carrying water and more time helping their families. “WASH is one of the major areas of focus of Rotary, and we are all encouraged as Clubs and Districts to focus as many of our projects as possible to address issues of supply of clean water, sanitation and hygiene in our communities.” On the need to maintain adequate hand wash and hygienic habits, Rotarian Femi Oloyede, District 9110, added that the scourge of the deadly disease can be curtailed by observing,’’ Wash your hands often; Use masks properly and when necessary; Have your temperature checked for fever; Avoid large crowds and stay home if you are sick and Never touch your face with unclean hands.’’ Oloyede stated, deliberate avoidance of unprotected contact with live animals and surfaces at markets and other public places should be maintained by individuals. Speaking on lassa fever, past district governor, Rotarian Deinde Shoga, said that there is no vaccine for the fever yet though a lot of research are ongoing. Shoga added that lassa fever should be handled like a public health emergency and massive awareness campaigns should be mounted by concerned authorities to prevent further illness and deaths. 